docs.abstract: When Dianne Feinstein was elected in 1992, only two women were in the U.S. Senate. There were 25 on the day she died.
docs.snippet: When Dianne Feinstein was elected in 1992, only two women were in the U.S. Senate. There were 25 on the day she died.
docs.lead_paragraph: Dianne Feinstein had several lifetimes’ worth of accomplishments by the time she died on Thursday at 90. She was pivotal in crafting a decade-long bipartisan assault weapons ban. She helped lead the congressional response to the Sept. 11 terrorist attacks and questioned the Central Intelligence Agency for its use of torture. As mayor of San Francisco, she led her hometown through years of tumult.

headline.main: Trailblazer, Role Model, Mentor: Feinstein’s Impact on Women in Office

docs.abstract: Our broken immigration system is still the best option for many migrants — and U.S. employers.
docs.snippet: Our broken immigration system is still the best option for many migrants — and U.S. employers.
docs.lead_paragraph: ‘We’re getting no support on this national crisis,’ Mayor Eric Adams said in September at a town-hall-style gathering on Manhattan’s Upper West Side. He was talking about the influx of transnational migrants who have landed in the city’s shelter system: more than 118,000 since the spring of last year, with about 10,000 more arriving each month. There are now about 115,000 people in the city’s care, and more than half of them are migrants. In August, the city projected that it would spend $5 billion caring for migrants during this fiscal year.

headline.main: Why Can’t We Stop Unauthorized Immigration? Because It Works.

docs.abstract: One of the rarest editions of The New York Times, from election night in 2000, never made it further than the newsroom.
docs.snippet: One of the rarest editions of The New York Times, from election night in 2000, never made it further than the newsroom.
docs.lead_paragraph: There is a lot of drama in a new history of The New York Times, “The Times: How the Newspaper of Record Survived Scandal, Scorn and the Transformation of Journalism,” by Adam Nagourney, a Times correspondent. Among the most anxious episodes was election night in 2000, which Mr. Nagourney called “a blur of changing headlines and stories rewritten in the space of minutes.”
